      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;operators-as-the-objects-of-study&#34; class=&#34;heading-anchor&#34;&gt;Operators as the objects of study&lt;a href=&#34;#operators-as-the-objects-of-study&#34; class=&#34;heading-link&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink to this section&#34; title=&#34;Copy link to this section&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;In finite dimensions, once you pick a basis, every linear map is a matrix. You can write it down, compute its eigenvalues, and go home. In infinite dimensions, &amp;ldquo;writing down&amp;rdquo; an operator is usually impossible, and the spectral theory is vastly richer. The first step: figure out which linear maps are well-behaved.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;figure class=&#34;article-figure&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;img src=&#34;https://blog-pic-ck.oss-cn-beijing.aliyuncs.com/posts/en/functional-analysis/03-bounded-operators/fa_fig3_operators.png?x-oss-process=image/format,webp/quality,q_85/resize,w_800&#34; alt=&#34;Bounded vs unbounded operators on normed spaces&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; decoding=&#34;async&#34; class=&#34;content-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
